Like many people I know, I always assumed that I would have 2 kids - a boy and a girl. I was growing up in a pretty big family with 3 younger siblings, and even though there were regular fights and arguments, we generally had a pretty good relationship. 

Unlike me, my husband had grown up as an only child. Despite all the ancient stereotypes about only children, he ended up becoming a pretty decent grown up haha, in fact, the most kind and generous person I know (after his mother). 

But one of the main reasons we've decided to have just one child is because parenthood is freaking HARD and I'll be the first one to admit that it's even harder than I thought it was. Oftentimes I feel like a failure for saying it out loud because there're so many families out there with 2+ (maybe even 5) kids and I know it has to be wayyyy harder, so technically I shouldn't complain. But it is what it is. Every family is different and I am working my way to accepting my reality, because I don't ever want to feel guilty for thinking that one kid is a handful. 

This decision makes perfect sense for us mentally, physically and financially right now and even though there's still a tiny hope that life will get easier in all of those aspects in order for us to get Markus a sibling, I still will be perfectly fine if we end up having just one child. 

Feel free to share your thoughts or experience on this slightly controversial subject. 😅

So yesterday was adventurous. Markus was sick and couldn't sleep very well, I found myself in his room every 40 minutes, and around 1 am I decided to stay and share a bed with him. Might as well, right?! Wrong! 😂

We've never shared a bed before, not even once. It just wasn't a thing for him and I'm glad cause I like my personal space, at least at night. 

Long story short, we didn't last very long. I woke up 20 minutes later when his elbow hit my face and that was it. I ended up going back to my bed and couldn't stop wondering HOW other parents can share a bed with their kids, even just occasionally?! 🤷🏼‍♀️ 

Are you one of those parents or you're more like me? I need to know 😂

Markus and I went to Walmart yesterday to grab a couple of things. I was standing in the greens section picking a salad for dinner, when he noticed a random bunch of bananas sitting right there in the middle.
He goes: 😮 "BANANAS in SALADS?! I have to put them back where they belong!"

(And he does that a lot when we go somewhere, always trying to fix a messy toy shelf and put things back in their bin...) My first thought was "it's nice of him, but they've got people working here, they'll fix it, we don't have to worry about it..." So I grabbed my salad and reminded him that we're in a hurry, but he insisted. 

At that moment I realized that his act of kindness should be supported and encouraged rather than the opposite. I guided him to the banana bins and he had the biggest smile on his face when he put the bunch where it was supposed to go. My child is kind and caring, and I definitely learn from him every day. If only every one of us did a small kind thing for another every time the opportunity presents itself, the world would be a better place🤍

Yesterday was a day that Markus and I will remember for a long time - at least I will! We spent all day exploring the local historical park, eating pizza and ice cream for lunch, petting farm animals and taking advantage of the amusement park on site, just the two of us. 

But here's where it gets interesting, I'm not a fan of amusement parks in general and a ferris wheel made me sweat quite a bit 😬. While it was a moment of joy for Markus, it was a moment of intense fear and pure anxiety for me! I was so scared to go on a ride, but I had to do it for him. Watching his face light up with excitement and happiness was worth every bit of my fear - which brings me to the main point.

In life, we often have to face our fears so our kids can have better lives. Taking that leap of faith and stepping out of our comfort zone can be the first step towards a brighter future for our little ones. Here's to all the brave parents out there who put their kids first and strive to give them the best life possible!

It's amazing how eager preschoolers are to help around the house! 🤗 That's why we make sure to give age appropriate chores and responsibilities to our little one to help him learn how to take care of himself and the world around him. 

From making their beds to helping sort out the recycling, it's never too early to start teaching kids about responsibility and self-care. Here's the ultimate list of age-appropriate chores and responsibilities for preschoolers:

• Make their bed without supervision
• Clear the table
• Pull weeds
• Use a hand-held vacuum for crumbs
• Water flowers
• Put away clean utensils 
• Wash plastic dishes with supervision
• Assist an older sibling or a family member with setting the table
• Help bring in light groceries
• Sort laundry into whites and colors before wash
• Match socks together
• Dust with a cloth
• Care for an animal's food and water

Cartoons with no dialogue require no cultural interpretation or language translation for children anywhere in the world. Here's some of our favorite ones:

1. The Mole/Krtek (Czech)

Created by Czech director and animator Zdeněk Miler in 1956, Krtek, or The Mole in English, was an international hit with children. Because the cartoons were presented with no dialogue, Krtek was held to no national boundaries. Watch on YouTube.

2. Pingu (Swiss-born)

Pingu is a clumsy young penguin who lives with his family on a polar ice cap in Antarctica. Pingu goes on adventures with his sister, Pinga, and his friend, Robby the seal. Pingu finds himself in tricky and comical situations, but he always learns a lesson. 

3. Shaun the Sheep (UK)

Shaun the Sheep thinks and acts like a person in a barnyard, which usually gets him into trouble. The farmer's sheepdog, Bitzer, tries to keep Shaun and his friends out of trouble. The farmer is oblivious to the human-like features of his flock, who are like one big, happy family.

4. Koulelo se Jablícko (Czech)

Koulelo se jablíčko is a Czechoslovak twenty-part animated evening series from 1989. The main characters of the series are the good worm Pepík and the hen. Watch on YouTube.

5. Piper (USA)

Piper is a 2016 computer-animated short film produced by Pixar Animation Studios. Pushed by her mother to become self-sufficient, a newly born sandpiper gains valuable life experience as she tries to overcome her fear of water.

Growing up with three siblings was certainly a blessing, but I've always wanted to have just one child of my own. For me, it's so important to be able to give my attention and resources to one kid and to spend as much quality time with them as possible. But I also know how special it is to have a sibling. 

So having kids 5 years apart sounds like a perfect solution for us, even though it wasn't an easy decision. They get to feel like the only child for a number of years, while I can be a better parent to each of them and still give them a sibling and a lifetime companion. 

Anyone out there with a bigger age gap between your kids? You're welcome to share your experience 👇🏻

TW: PPROM - unknown outcome

The last few days have been a rollercoaster of emotions. After so many weeks of a seemingly healthy pregnancy, my water broke a day before I was halfway through and I was sent to the hospital by an ambulance.

The prognosis is poor for the baby to survive this early, I'm doing all I can to prolong the pregnancy and staying positive, but at this point the outcome is still unknown. 

All I can ask for in this difficult time is your thoughts and prayers.🙏🏻

Even though the holidays won't be quite the same this year, I'm still grateful for the small things. 
This pregnancy did not go the way I expected, I never got to experience the third trimester and my baby is in the NICU right now, so joy seems far away...
But at least I'm healthy and my baby is healthy, and so is everyone else in my family, so I'm holding on to that. 
It's easy to get overwhelmed but it's important to take a step back and appreciate the little things. This year, the holidays might look different, but one day I'll look back and it all will be a distant memory.

Let's talk about the unexpected reality of premature birth. It's a journey that no one plans for, yet so many parents have to face. It's a reminder that even with all the preparation in the world, life can throw you a curveball. 

But that's okay, because these preemies are strong, tough, resilient, courageous, fighters and miracles all rolled into one. And NICU parents are strong enough to handle it all. 

To all the parents out there who never imagined having a premature baby, know that you're not alone. Keep holding on, we've got this. 🫶🏻

Snowflakes may be falling elsewhere, but here in December, we're feeling the warmth! While we're all soaking up these beautiful days, a tiny part of me is still dreaming of a white Christmas. But until then, I'll be living vicariously through Markus and his adventurous spirit. He's making the most of this little patch of snow that's hanging on for dear life, because who knows if it'll still be there tomorrow?!
Born at just 26 weeks our little miracle is growing, thriving and is the best Christmas present we could ever wish for 🤍

Reflecting back on this year, I can't help but feel a wave of emotions...

From the excitement of expecting our second child to the fear of the unknown as we faced complications during this pregnancy, to the overwhelming pride and joy of holding my beautiful baby in my arms. 

It's been a rollercoaster of a journey, but through it all, I've learned the true meaning of strength, love, and resilience. As we enter 2024, I can't wait to see what's in store for us. With a full heart and open mind, I'm ready to embrace whatever comes our way. Here's to another year of growth, love, and endless blessings. 🥂

Happy New Year, friends! 🍾 🎊

We often think of progress as a straight line, moving steadily forward. But as we navigate our NICU journey, I'm reminded every day that it's not always that simple. There are ups and downs, twists and turns, and some days it can be hard to see the light at the end of the tunnel... 

But in those moments, I hold onto the little victories, the tiny steps forward, and I celebrate them with all my heart. Because even though the road may not be straight, every small win is a reminder of how far we've come and how much we've overcome. And that is definitely worth celebrating.
